[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Several methods have been devised that increase the effectiveness of memory management.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Virtual memory systems separate the memory addresses used by a process from actual physical addresses, allowing separation of processes and increasing the size of the virtual address space beyond the available amount of RAM using paging or swapping to secondary storage.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The quality of the virtual memory manager can have an extensive effect on overall system performance.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The system allows a computer to appear as if it may have more memory available than physically present, thereby allowing multiple processes to share it.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Burroughs/Unisys MCP, and OS/360 and successors, memory is managed by the operating system.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Unix-like operating systems, memory is managed at the application level.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Memory management within an address space is generally categorized as either manual memory management or automatic memory management.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The task of fulfilling an allocation request consists of locating a block of unused memory of sufficient size.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Memory requests are satisfied by allocating portions from a large pool of memory called the *heap* or *free store*.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] At any given time, some parts of the heap are in use, while some are "free" (unused) and thus available for future allocations.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] In the C language, the function which allocates memory from the heap is called `malloc` and the function which takes previously allocated memory and marks it as "free" (to be used by future allocations) is called `free`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Several issues complicate the implementation, such as external fragmentation, which arises when there are many small gaps between allocated memory blocks, which invalidates their use for an allocation request.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The allocator's metadata can also inflate the size of (individually) small allocations.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The memory management system must track outstanding allocations to ensure that they do not overlap and that no memory is ever "lost" (i.e. that there are no "memory leaks").
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The specific dynamic memory allocation algorithm implemented can impact performance significantly.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] A study conducted in 1994 by Digital Equipment Corporation illustrates the overheads involved for a variety of allocators.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The lowest average instruction path length required to allocate a single memory slot was 52 (as measured with an instruction level profiler on a variety of software).
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Since the precise location of the allocation is not known in advance, the memory is accessed indirectly, usually through a pointer reference.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Fixed-size blocks allocation, also called memory pool allocation, uses a free list of fixed-size blocks of memory (often all of the same size).
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] This works well for simple embedded systems where no large objects need to be allocated but suffers from fragmentation especially with long memory addresses.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] However, due to the significantly reduced overhead, this method can substantially improve performance for objects that need frequent allocation and deallocation, and so it is often used in video games.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] In this system, memory is allocated into several pools of memory instead of just one, where each pool represents blocks of memory of a certain power of two in size, or blocks of some other convenient size progression.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] All blocks of a particular size are kept in a sorted linked list or tree and all new blocks that are formed during allocation are added to their respective memory pools for later use.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] If a smaller size is requested than is available, the smallest available size is selected and split.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] When a block is split, it is divided into two smaller blocks, and each smaller block becomes a unique "buddy" to the other.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] One of the resulting parts is selected, and the process repeats until the request is complete.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] When a block is allocated, the allocator will start with the smallest sufficiently large block to avoid needlessly breaking blocks.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] When a block is freed, it is compared to its buddy.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] If they are both free, they are combined and placed in the correspondingly larger-sized buddy-block list.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] This memory allocation mechanism preallocates memory chunks suitable to fit objects of a certain type or size.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] These chunks are called caches and the allocator only has to keep track of a list of free cache slots.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Constructing an object will use any one of the free cache slots and destructing an object will add a slot back to the free cache slot list.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] This technique alleviates memory fragmentation and is efficient as there is no need to search for a suitable portion of memory, as any open slot will suffice.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Many Unix-like systems as well as Microsoft Windows implement a function called `alloca` for dynamically allocating stack memory in a way similar to the heap-based `malloc`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] A compiler typically translates it to inlined instructions manipulating the stack pointer.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Although there is no need of manually freeing memory allocated this way, as it is automatically freed when the function that called `alloca` returns, there exists a risk of overflow.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] And since alloca is an *ad hoc* expansion seen in many systems but never in POSIX or the C standard, its behavior in case of a stack overflow is undefined.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] A safer version of alloca called `_malloca`, which reports errors, exists on Microsoft Windows.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] It requires the use of `_freea`. gnulib provides an equivalent interface, albeit instead of throwing an SEH exception on overflow, it delegates to malloc when an overlarge size is detected.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] A similar feature can be emulated using manual accounting and size-checking, such as in the uses of `alloca_account` in glibc.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The proper management of memory in an application is a difficult problem, and several different strategies for handling memory management have been devised.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Special declarations may allow local variables to retain values between invocations of the procedure, or may allow local variables to be accessed by other subroutines.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The automatic allocation of local variables makes recursion possible, to a depth limited by available memory.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Garbage collection is a strategy for automatically detecting memory allocated to objects that are no longer usable in a program, and returning that allocated memory to a pool of free memory locations.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] This method is in contrast to "manual" memory management where a programmer explicitly codes memory requests and memory releases in the program.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] While automatic garbage collection has the advantages of reducing programmer workload and preventing certain kinds of memory allocation bugs, garbage collection does require memory resources of its own, and can compete with the application program for processor time.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Reference counting is a strategy for detecting that memory is no longer usable by a program by maintaining a counter for how many independent pointers point to the memory.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Whenever a new pointer points to a piece of memory, the programmer is supposed to increase the counter.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] When the pointer changes where it points, or when the pointer is no longer pointing to any area or has itself been freed, the counter should decrease.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] When the counter drops to zero, the memory should be considered unused and freed.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Some reference counting systems require programmer involvement and some are implemented automatically by the compiler.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] A disadvantage of reference counting is that circular references can develop which cause a memory leak to occur.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] This can be mitigated by either adding the concept of a "weak reference" (a reference that does not participate in reference counting, but is notified when the area it is pointing to is no longer valid) or by combining reference counting and garbage collection together.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] A memory pool is a technique of automatically deallocating memory based on the state of the application, such as the lifecycle of a request or transaction.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The idea is that many applications execute large chunks of code which may generate memory allocations, but that there is a point in execution where all of those chunks are known to be no longer valid.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] For example, in a web service, after each request the web service no longer needs any of the memory allocated during the execution of the request.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Therefore, rather than keeping track of whether or not memory is currently being referenced, the memory is allocated according to the request or lifecycle stage with which it is associated.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] When that request or stage has passed, all associated memory is deallocated simultaneously.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Virtual memory is a method of decoupling the memory organization from the physical hardware.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The applications operate on memory via *virtual addresses*.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Each attempt by the application to access a particular virtual memory address results in the virtual memory address being translated to an actual *physical address*.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] In this way the addition of virtual memory enables granular control over memory systems and methods of access.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] In virtual memory systems the operating system limits how a process can access the memory.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] This feature, called memory protection, can be used to disallow a process to read or write to memory that is not allocated to it, preventing malicious or malfunctioning code in one program from interfering with the operation of another.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Even though the memory allocated for specific processes is normally isolated, processes sometimes need to be able to share information.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Shared memory is one of the fastest techniques for inter-process communication.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Memory is usually classified by access rate into primary storage and secondary storage.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Memory management systems, among other operations, also handle the moving of information between these two levels of memory.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] An operating system manages various resources in the computing system.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The memory subsystem is the system element for managing memory.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The memory subsystem combines the hardware memory resource and the MCP OS software that manages the resource.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The memory subsystem manages the physical memory and the virtual memory of the system (both part of the hardware resource).
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The virtual memory extends physical memory by using extra space on a peripheral device, usually disk.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for moving code and data between main and virtual memory in a process known as overlaying.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Burroughs was the first commercial implementation of virtual memory (although developed at Manchester University for the Ferranti Atlas computer) and integrated virtual memory with the system design of the B5000 from the start (in 1961) needing no external memory management unit (MMU).
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for mapping logical requests for memory blocks to physical portions of memory (segments) which are found in the list of free segments.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Descriptors are essential in providing memory safety and security so that operations cannot overflow or underflow the referenced block (commonly known as buffer overflow).
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Descriptors themselves are protected control words that cannot be manipulated except for specific elements of the MCP OS (enabled by the UNSAFE block directive in NEWP).
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Donald Knuth describes a similar system in Section 2.5 ‘Dynamic Storage Allocation’ of ‘Fundamental Algorithms’.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] IBM System/360 does not support virtual memory.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Memory isolation of jobs is optionally accomplished using protection keys, assigning storage for each job a different key, 0 for the supervisor or 1–15.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Memory management in OS/360 is a supervisor function.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Storage is requested using the `GETMAIN` macro and freed using the `FREEMAIN` macro, which result in a call to the supervisor (SVC) to perform the operation.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] In OS/360 the details vary depending on how the system is generated, e.g., for PCP, MFT, MVT.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] In OS/360 MVT, suballocation within a job's *region* or the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is based on *subpools*, areas a multiple of 2 KB in size—the size of an area protected by a protection key.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Within a region subpools are assigned either the job's storage protection or the supervisor's key, key 0.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Initially only subpool zero is created, and all user storage requests are satisfied from subpool 0, unless another is specified in the memory request.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Subpools 250–255 are created by memory requests by the supervisor on behalf of the job.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Most of these are assigned key 0, although a few get the key of the job.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Subpool numbers are also relevant in MFT, although the details are much simpler.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] MFT uses fixed *partitions* redefinable by the operator instead of dynamic regions and PCP has only a single partition.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Each subpool is mapped by a list of control blocks identifying allocated and free memory blocks within the subpool.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Memory is allocated by finding a free area of sufficient size, or by allocating additional blocks in the subpool, up to the region size of the job.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] It is possible to free all or part of an allocated memory area.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] The details for OS/VS1 are similar to those for MFT and for MVT; the details for OS/VS2 are similar to those for MVT, except that the page size is 4 KiB.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] For both OS/VS1 and OS/VS2 the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is nonpageable.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] In MVS the address space includes an additional pageable shared area, the *Common Storage Area* (CSA), and two additional private areas, the nonpageable *local system queue area* (LSQA) and the pageable *System Work area* (SWA).
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-management] Also, the storage keys 0–7 are all reserved for use by privileged code.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Memory errors were first considered in the context of resource management (computing) and time-sharing systems, in an effort to avoid problems such as fork bombs.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Developments were mostly theoretical until the Morris worm, which exploited a buffer overflow in fingerd.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] The field of computer security developed quickly thereafter, escalating with multitudes of new attacks such as the return-to-libc attack and defense techniques such as the non-executable stack and address space layout randomization.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Randomization prevents most buffer overflow attacks and requires the attacker to use heap spraying or other application-dependent methods to obtain addresses, although its adoption has been slow.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] However, deployments of the technology are typically limited to randomizing libraries and the location of the stack.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] In 2019, a Microsoft security engineer reported that 70% of all security vulnerabilities were caused by memory safety issues.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] In 2020, a team at Google similarly reported that 70% of all "severe security bugs" in Chromium were caused by memory safety problems.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Many other high-profile vulnerabilities and exploits in critical software have ultimately stemmed from a lack of memory safety, including Heartbleed and a long-standing privilege escalation bug in sudo.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] The pervasiveness and severity of vulnerabilities and exploits arising from memory safety issues have led several security researchers to describe identifying memory safety issues as "shooting fish in a barrel".
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Some modern high-level programming languages are memory-safe by default, though not completely since they only check their own code and not the system they interact with.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Automatic memory management in the form of garbage collection is the most common technique for preventing some of the memory safety problems, since it prevents common memory safety errors like use-after-free for all data allocated within the language runtime.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] However, the performance overhead of garbage collection makes these languages unsuitable for certain performance-critical applications.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] For languages that use manual memory management, memory safety is not usually guaranteed by the runtime.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Instead, memory safety properties must either be guaranteed by the compiler via static program analysis and automated theorem proving or carefully managed by the programmer at runtime.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] For example, the Rust programming language implements a borrow checker to ensure memory safety, while C and C++ provide no memory safety guarantees.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] The substantial amount of software written in C and C++ has motivated the development of external static analysis tools like Coverity, which offers static memory analysis for C.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] DieHard, its redesign DieHarder, and the Allinea Distributed Debugging Tool are special heap allocators that allocate objects in their own random virtual memory page, allowing invalid reads and writes to be stopped and debugged at the exact instruction that causes them.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Protection relies upon hardware memory protection and thus overhead is typically not substantial, although it can grow significantly if the program makes heavy use of allocation.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Randomization provides only probabilistic protection against memory errors, but can often be easily implemented in existing software by relinking the binary.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] The memcheck tool of Valgrind uses an instruction set simulator and runs the compiled program in a memory-checking virtual machine, providing guaranteed detection of a subset of runtime memory errors.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] However, it typically slows the program down by a factor of 40, and furthermore must be explicitly informed of custom memory allocators.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] With access to the source code, libraries exist that collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity, such as the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] In general, memory safety can be safely assured using tracing garbage collection and the insertion of runtime checks on every memory access; this approach has overhead, but less than that of Valgrind.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] All garbage-collected languages take this approach.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] For C and C++, many tools exist that perform a compile-time transformation of the code to do memory safety checks at runtime, such as CheckPointer and AddressSanitizer which imposes an average slowdown factor of 2.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] BoundWarden is a new spatial memory enforcement approach that utilizes a combination of compile-time transformation and runtime concurrent monitoring techniques.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Fuzz testing is well-suited for finding memory safety bugs and is often used in combination with dynamic checkers such as AddressSanitizer.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Some lists may also include **race conditions** (concurrent reads/writes to shared memory) as being part of memory safety (e.g., for access control).
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] The Rust programming language prevents many kinds of memory-based race conditions by default, because it ensures there is at most one writer *or* one or more readers.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Many other programming languages, such as Java, do *not* automatically prevent memory-based race conditions, yet are still generally considered "memory safe" languages.
[src:rust-memory-safety/memory-safety] Therefore, countering race conditions is generally *not* considered necessary for a language to be considered memory safe.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] In computer science, **region-based memory management** is a type of memory management in which each allocated object is assigned to a **region**.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] A region, also called a **partition**, **subpool**, **zone**, **arena**, **area**, or **memory context**, is a collection of allocated objects that can be efficiently reallocated or deallocated all at once.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Memory allocators using region-based managements are often called **area allocators**, and when they work by only "bumping" a single pointer, as **bump allocators**.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Like stack allocation, regions facilitate allocation and deallocation of memory with low overhead; but they are more flexible, allowing objects to live longer than the stack frame in which they were allocated.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] In typical implementations, all objects in a region are allocated in a single contiguous range of memory addresses, similarly to how stack frames are typically allocated.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] In OS/360 and successors, the concept applies at two levels; each job runs within a contiguous partition or region.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Storage allocation requests specify a subpool, and the application can free an entire subpool.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Storage for a subpool is allocated from the region or partition in blocks that are a multiple of 2 KiB or 4 KiB that generally are not contiguous.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] As a simple example, consider the following C++ code, which implements a simple compile-time arena, and a simple data type consisting of a string and an integer value.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Simple explicit regions are straightforward to implement; the following description is based on the work of Hanson.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Each region is implemented as a linked list of large blocks of memory; each block should be large enough to serve many allocations.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] The current block maintains a pointer to the next free position in the block, and if the block is filled, a new one is allocated and added to the list.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] When the region is deallocated, the next-free-position pointer is reset to the beginning of the first block, and the list of blocks can be reused for the next allocated region.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Alternatively, when a region is deallocated, its list of blocks can be appended to a global freelist from which other regions may later allocate new blocks.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] With either case of this simple scheme, it is not possible to deallocate individual objects in regions.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] The overall cost per allocated byte of this scheme is very low; almost all allocations involve only a comparison and an update to the next-free-position pointer.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Deallocating a region is a constant-time operation, and is done rarely.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Unlike in typical garbage collection systems, there is no need to tag data with its type.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] The basic concept of regions is very old, first appearing as early as 1967 in Douglas T.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Ross's AED Free Storage Package, in which memory was partitioned into a hierarchy of zones; each zone had its own allocator, and a zone could be freed all-at-once, making zones usable as regions.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] In 1976, the PL/I standard included the AREA data type.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] In 1990, Hanson demonstrated that explicit regions in C (which he called arenas) could achieve time performance per allocated byte superior to even the fastest-known heap allocation mechanism.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Explicit regions were instrumental in the design of some early C-based software projects, including the Apache HTTP Server, which calls them pools, and the PostgreSQL database management system, which calls them memory contexts.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Like traditional heap allocation, these schemes do not provide memory safety; it is possible for a programmer to access a region after it is deallocated through a dangling pointer, or to forget to deallocate a region, causing a memory leak.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] The compiler is able to do this in such a way that it can guarantee dangling pointers and leaks do not occur.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] In an early work by Ruggieri and Murtagh, a region is created at the beginning of each function and deallocated at the end.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] They then use data flow analysis to determine a lifetime for each static allocation expression, and assign it to the youngest region that contains its entire lifetime.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Due to this syntactic structure, regions are *nested*, meaning that if $r_{2}$ is created after $r_{1}$ , it must also be deallocated before $r_{1}$ ; the result is a *stack* of regions.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Moreover, regions must be deallocated in the same function in which they are created.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] These restrictions were relaxed by Aiken et al.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] This work was completed in 1995 and integrated into the ML Kit, a version of ML based on region allocation in place of garbage collection.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] This permitted a direct comparison between the two on medium-sized test programs, yielding widely varying results ("between 10 times faster and four times slower") depending on how "region-friendly" the program was; compile times, however, were on the order of minutes.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] The ML Kit was eventually scaled to large applications with two additions: a scheme for separate compilation of modules, and a hybrid technique combining region inference with tracing garbage collection.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Systems using regions may experience issues where regions become very large before they are deallocated and contain a large proportion of dead data; these are commonly called "leaks" (even though they are eventually freed).
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Eliminating leaks may involve restructuring the program, typically by introducing new, shorter-lifetime regions.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Debugging this type of problem is especially difficult in systems using region inference, where the programmer must understand the underlying inference algorithm, or examine the verbose intermediate representation, to diagnose the issue.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Tracing garbage collectors are more effective at deallocating this type of data in a timely manner without program changes; this was one justification for hybrid region/GC systems.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] On the other hand, tracing garbage collectors can also exhibit subtle leaks, if references are retained to data which will never be used again.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Region-based memory management works best when the number of regions is relatively small and each contains many objects; programs that contain many sparse regions will exhibit internal fragmentation, leading to wasted memory and a time overhead for region management.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Again, in the presence of region inference this problem can be more difficult to diagnose.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] As mentioned above, RC uses a hybrid of regions and reference counting, limiting the overhead of reference counting since references internal to regions don't require counts to be updated when they're modified.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] Similarly, some *mark-region* hybrid methods combine tracing garbage collection with regions; these function by dividing the heap into regions, performing a mark-sweep pass in which any regions containing live objects are marked, and then freeing any unmarked regions.
[src:rust-memory-safety/region-based-memory-management] These require continual defragmentation to remain effective.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII is associated most prominently with C++, where it originated, but also Ada, Vala, and Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The technique was developed for exception-safe resource management in C++ during 1984–1989, primarily by Bjarne Stroustrup and Andrew Koenig, and the term itself was coined by Stroustrup.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Other names for this idiom include *Constructor Acquires, Destructor Releases* (CADRe) and one particular style of use is called *Scope-based Resource Management* (SBRM).
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This latter term is for the special case of automatic variables.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII ties resources to object *lifetime,* which may not coincide with entry and exit of a scope.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] (Notably variables allocated on the free store have lifetimes unrelated to any given scope.) However, using RAII for automatic variables (SBRM) is the most common use case.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This code is exception-safe because C++ guarantees that all objects with automatic storage duration (local variables) are destroyed at the end of the enclosing scope in the reverse order of their construction.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The destructors of both the *lock* and *file* objects are therefore guaranteed to be called when returning from the function, whether an exception has been thrown or not.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Local variables allow easy management of multiple resources within a single function: they are destroyed in the reverse order of their construction, and an object is destroyed only if fully constructed—that is, if no exception propagates from its constructor.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Using RAII greatly simplifies resource management, reduces overall code size and helps ensure program correctness.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII is therefore recommended by industry-standard guidelines, and most of the C++ standard library follows the idiom.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The advantages of RAII as a resource management technique are that it provides encapsulation, exception safety (for stack resources), and locality (it allows acquisition and release logic to be written next to each other).
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Encapsulation is provided because resource management logic is defined once in the class, not at each call site.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Finally, locality of definition is provided by writing the constructor and destructor definitions next to each other in the class definition.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Resource management therefore needs to be tied to the lifespan of suitable objects in order to gain automatic allocation and reclamation.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Resources are acquired during initialization, when there is no chance of them being used before they are available, and released with the destruction of the same objects, which is guaranteed to take place even in case of errors.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] As a class invariant, RAII provides guarantees that an object instance that is supposed to have acquired a resource has in fact done so.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The RAII design is often used for controlling mutex locks in multi-threaded applications.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In that use, the object releases the lock when destroyed.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Without RAII in this scenario the potential for deadlock would be high and the logic to lock the mutex would be far from the logic to unlock it.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] With RAII, the code that locks the mutex essentially includes the logic that the lock will be released when execution leaves the scope of the RAII object.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Another typical example is interacting with files: We could have an object that represents a file that is open for writing, wherein the file is opened in the constructor and closed when execution leaves the object's scope.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In both cases, RAII ensures only that the resource in question is released appropriately; care must still be taken to maintain exception safety.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] If the code modifying the data structure or file is not exception-safe, the mutex could be unlocked or the file closed with the data structure or file corrupted.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Ownership of dynamically allocated objects (memory allocated with `new` in C++) can also be controlled with RAII, such that the object is released when the RAII (stack-based) object is destroyed.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] For this purpose, the C++11 standard library defines the smart pointer classes `std::unique_ptr` for single-owned objects and `std::shared_ptr` for objects with shared ownership.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Similar classes are also available through `std::auto_ptr` in C++98, and `boost::shared_ptr` in the Boost libraries.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Also, messages can be sent to network resources using RAII.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In this case, the RAII object would send a message to a socket at the end of the constructor, when its initialization is completed.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] It would also send a message at the beginning of the destructor, when the object is about to be destroyed.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Such a construct might be used in a client object to establish a connection with a server running in another process.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In many languages that lack direct memory management or discourage its use, a similar mechanism called the "dispose pattern" is used to call a `dispose` method that performs relevant resource cleanup on the object at the end of scope.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] For versions of C prior to the introduction of `defer` Clang and the GNU Compiler Collection implement a `[[gnu::cleanup]]` attribute as a non-standard extension to C.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In this example, the compiler arranges for the `fclosep` function to be called on `logFile` before `writeLogFile` returns.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In C++, disposing is done directly with a destructor.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In C++, a class `X` will automatically call its destructor `~X()` when it reaches the end of scope.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] The dispose pattern is essentially equivalent to RAII in C++.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] C# features a `using`-with-resources block, which can be used if the object implements `System.IDisposable`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] It will call a `Dispose()` method at the end of the resource.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Java features a `try`-with-resources block, which can be used if the object implements `java.lang.AutoCloseable`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] It will call a `close()` method at the end of the resource.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Python features a `with` block, which can be used if the object implements `__enter__` and `__exit__` methods.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This is also used for managing resources such as locks.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Rust allows defining custom cleanup logic, if an object implements `std::ops::Drop`, which will call a `drop()` method after the object leaves scope.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This can also be manually called by `std::mem::drop()`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII only works for resources acquired and released (directly or indirectly) by stack-allocated objects, where there *is* a well-defined static object lifetime.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Heap-allocated objects which themselves acquire and release resources are common in many languages, including C++.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] RAII depends on heap-based objects to be implicitly or explicitly deleted along all possible execution paths, in order to trigger its resource-releasing destructor (or equivalent).
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This can be achieved by using smart pointers to manage all heap objects, with weak pointers for cyclically referenced objects.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In C++, stack unwinding is only guaranteed to occur if the exception is caught somewhere.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This is because "If no matching handler is found in a program, the function terminate() is called; whether or not the stack is unwound before this call to terminate() is implementation-defined (15.5.1)." (C++03 standard, §15.3/9).
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This behavior is usually acceptable, since the operating system releases remaining resources like memory, files, sockets, etc. at program termination.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] At the 2018 Gamelab conference, Jonathan Blow claimed that use of RAII can cause memory fragmentation which in turn can cause cache misses and a 100 times or worse hit on performance.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Perl, Python (in the CPython implementation), and PHP manage object lifetime by reference counting, which makes it possible to use RAII.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Objects that are no longer referenced are immediately destroyed or finalized and released, so a destructor or finalizer can release the resource at that time.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] However, it is not always idiomatic in such languages, and is specifically discouraged in Python (in favor of context managers and *finalizers* from the *weakref* package).
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] However, object lifetimes are not necessarily bound to any scope, and objects may be destroyed non-deterministically or not at all.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] This makes it possible to accidentally leak resources that should have been released at the end of some scope.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Objects stored in a static variable (notably a global variable) may not be finalized when the program terminates, so their resources are not released; CPython makes no guarantee of finalizing such objects, for instance.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] Further, objects with circular references will not be collected by a simple reference counter, and will live indeterminately long; even if collected (by more sophisticated garbage collection), destruction time and destruction order will be non-deterministic.
[src:rust-memory-safety/resource-acquisition-is-initialization] In CPython there is a cycle detector which detects cycles and finalizes the objects in the cycle, though prior to CPython 3.4, cycles are not collected if any object in the cycle has a finalizer.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:rust-memory-safety/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] The Clean programming language makes use of uniqueness types (a variant of linear types) to help support concurrency, input/output, and in-place update of arrays.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Linear type systems allow references but not aliases.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] To enforce this, a reference goes out of scope after appearing on the right-hand side of an assignment, thus ensuring that only one reference to any object exists at once.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Note that passing a reference as an argument to a function is a form of assignment, as the function parameter will be assigned the value inside the function, and therefore such use of a reference also causes it to go out of scope.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] The single-reference property makes linear type systems suitable as programming languages for quantum computing, as it reflects the no-cloning theorem of quantum states.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] From the category theory point of view, no-cloning is a statement that there is no diagonal functor which could duplicate states; similarly, from the combinatory logic point of view, there is no K-combinator which can destroy states.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] From the lambda calculus point of view, a variable `x` can appear exactly once in a term.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Linear type systems are the internal language of closed symmetric monoidal categories, much in the same way that simply typed lambda calculus is the language of Cartesian closed categories.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] More precisely, one may construct functors between the category of linear type systems and the category of closed symmetric monoidal categories.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] The nomenclature offered by substructural type systems is useful to characterize resource management aspects of a language.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Resource management is the aspect of language safety concerned with ensuring that each allocated resource is deallocated exactly once.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Thus, **the resource interpretation** is only concerned with uses that transfer ownership – *moving*, where ownership is the responsibility to free the resource.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Uses that don't transfer ownership – *borrowing* – are not in scope of this interpretation, but *lifetime semantics* further restrict these uses to be between allocation and deallocation.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Under the resource interpretation, an *affine* type cannot be spent more than once.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] In other words, an affine type system can express the typestate pattern: Functions can consume and return an object wrapped in different types, acting like state transitions in a state machine that stores its state as a type in the caller's context – a *typestate*.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] An API can exploit this to statically enforce that its functions are called in a correct order.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] What Rust is not able to express is a coin type that cannot go out of scope – that would take a linear type.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Under the resource interpretation, a *linear* type not only *can* be moved, like an affine type, but *must* be moved – going out of scope is an invalid program.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] An attraction with linear types is that destructors become regular functions that can take arguments, can fail and so on.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] This may for example avoid the need to keep state that is only used for destruction.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] A general advantage of passing function dependencies explicitly is that the order of function calls – destruction order – becomes statically verifiable in terms of the arguments' lifetimes.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Compared to internal references, this does not require lifetime annotations as in Rust.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] As with manual resource management, a practical problem is that any early return, as is typical of error handling, must achieve the same cleanup.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] This becomes pedantic in languages that have stack unwinding, where every function call is a potential early return.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] However, as a close analogy, the semantic of implicitly inserted destructor calls can be restored with deferred function calls.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] Under the resource interpretation, a *normal* type does not restrict how many times a variable can be moved from.
[src:rust-memory-safety/substructural-type-system] C++ (specifically nondestructive move semantics) falls in this category.
